# jira-helper

A terminal **CLI** and importable **Python library** for admin work over
**Atlassian Cloud** (Jira today, Confluence later): resolve people ↔ Atlassian
account-ids, manage virtual teams, and query/cache tickets (including
parent-relationship trees) for fast browsing, statistics, and reports.

> **Status: early release.** The core workflow is live — onboard with `init`,
> map people with `account`, and query tickets with `issue list`/`issue get`.
> Advanced features (virtual teams, parent-tree `roots`/`tree`, custom rules,
> background `sync`, Confluence) are still landing and report *not implemented*
> for now. The full command surface is wired and self-describing (`--help`,
> `spec`); the shape is stable and the behavior fills in.

## Design

- **Library-first, 1:1 mapping.** Every command is a thin wrapper over a
  function: `noun` = module, `verb` = function. `jira-helper issue roots …` →
  `jira_helper.issue.roots(…)`. The CLI only parses args and renders; `--json`
  is a renderer flag, never a behavior change.
- **Resource-first nouns** modeled on `gh`/`kubectl`:
  `jira-helper [GLOBAL FLAGS] <noun> <verb> [args] [flags]`.
- **`--json` everywhere** for scripting, plus a machine-readable `spec` command
  that emits the entire command tree (every command, arg, flag, type, default)
  as JSON — built to be driven by an LLM/MCP wrapper.

## Command surface

```
jira-helper init | doctor | version          # onboarding, health, version
jira-helper spec [--json]                     # full command tree (LLM/MCP ingest)

jira-helper config  init|show|get|set|edit|verify|path
jira-helper account list|get|add|remove|search|path     # name ↔ account-id
jira-helper issue   list|roots|tree|get                 # ticket queries
jira-helper team    list|show|create|delete|rename|add-member|remove-member|path
jira-helper rule    list|edit|add|remove|test|validate|path   # virtual-parent rules
jira-helper cache   status|get|export|clear|path        # local SQLite cache
jira-helper sync    run|status|install                  # background refresh
```

Global flags are defined once and precede the noun, e.g.
`jira-helper --json issue list --assignee alice`.

Run `jira-helper --help` (or `<noun> --help`) for the full, documented grammar.

## Quick start

```bash
# 1. onboard (writes ~/.config/jira-helper/config.yaml, chmod 600)
jira-helper init

# 2. confirm credentials + cache health
jira-helper doctor

# 3. map a person to their Atlassian account-id
jira-helper account search "Alice Kim"           # live lookup → candidate ids
jira-helper account add alice 5b10ac8d82e05b22cc  # record the mapping

# 4. query tickets
jira-helper issue list --assignee alice                 # one person
jira-helper issue list --assignee alice --assignee bob  # several
jira-helper issue list --created-from 2024-01-01 --created-to 2024-03-31
jira-helper issue list --jql 'project = PROJA AND statusCategory != Done'
jira-helper issue get PROJA-123
jira-helper --json issue list --assignee alice          # machine-readable
```

## Use as a library

```python
import jira_helper

jira_helper.account.add("alice", "5b10ac8d82e05b22cc")
issues = jira_helper.issue.list(assignee=["alice"])
one = jira_helper.issue.get("PROJA-123")
```

## Requirements

- Python 3.11+
- A Jira Cloud site (`https://your-domain.atlassian.net`)
- A Jira API token — create one at
  <https://id.atlassian.com/manage-profile/security/api-tokens>

## Installation

### Install / update (recommended)

[`uv`](https://docs.astral.sh/uv/) installs the tool from a public distribution
index over plain, anonymous HTTPS — no GitHub login or token required (handy on
locked-down networks where authenticated access is blocked). First install `uv`:

```bash
curl -LsSf https://astral.sh/uv/install.sh | sh
```

Then install — and later upgrade — `jira-helper`:

```bash
# install
uv tool install jira-helper --index https://xohzzwn6kcj9.github.io/gh-dist/simple/

# upgrade to the latest release
uv tool install --force jira-helper --index https://xohzzwn6kcj9.github.io/gh-dist/simple/
```

For one-word upgrades, add an alias to `~/.zshrc`:

```bash
alias jh-up='uv tool install --force jira-helper --index https://xohzzwn6kcj9.github.io/gh-dist/simple/'
```

`--index` keeps PyPI as the default, so runtime dependencies (typer, httpx,
PyYAML) resolve from PyPI while `jira-helper` itself comes from the distribution
index. This assumes PyPI is reachable over HTTPS.

### From a clone (development)

```bash
pip install -e .
```

Either way you get the `jira-helper` console entry point.

## Configuration

Authentication uses Jira Cloud **basic auth** with your account email + an API
token (the token is **not** your password). Two ways to provide it, in order of
precedence:

1. **Interactive** — `jira-helper init` writes `config.yaml` (chmod 600) under
   `$JIRA_HELPER_CONFIG` → `~/.config/jira-helper/`. Inspect/edit it later with
   `jira-helper config show` / `config set <key> <value>` / `config verify`.
2. **Environment variables** — override (or replace) the file at read time:

   | Variable         | Description                              |
   | ---------------- | ---------------------------------------- |
   | `JIRA_BASE_URL`  | e.g. `https://your-domain.atlassian.net` |
   | `JIRA_EMAIL`     | The Atlassian account email              |
   | `JIRA_API_TOKEN` | API token (NOT your password)            |

Env vars win over the file, so CI or a throwaway shell can run without `init`.

> Never commit credentials. The config file and `.env` are git-ignored, and the
> token is masked by `config show`/`get` unless you pass `--reveal`.

## Development

```bash
pip install -e '.[dev]'
ruff check .
ruff format .
pytest
```

## Releasing (maintainer)

The version is derived from git tags by `setuptools-scm`, so a tag push **is** the
release: GitHub Actions builds the wheel and publishes it to the distribution
index over GitHub Pages.

```bash
git tag v0.2.0
git push origin v0.2.0
```
